he founding of cities, to paint a dynamic picture of the genesis of renewed political life in the Andean region. Examining how missionaries, soldiers, native lords, and other writers employed classical concepts to forge new understandings of Peruvian society and history, the book offers a complete reassessment of the ways in which colonial Peru made the classical heritage uniquely its own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aIncas in literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aIncasxFirst contact with Europeans. 0aIncasxFirst contact with other peoples. 0aIncasxHistoriography. 0aIndian literaturezAndes RegionxHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish literaturezAndes RegionxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh  aAeneid.  aAlcalde.  aAlfonso X of Castile.  aAmericas.  aAmun.  aAncient Rome.  aAndean civilizations.  aAndes.  aArrival and Departure.  aAspromonte.  aAtahualpa.  aAtaulf.  aAtoll.  aBartolomé de las Casas.  aCaesar and Pompey.  aCaprera.  aCesarea.  aChronology.  aCircumnavigation.  aClassical antiquity.  aClassical tradition.  aClime.  aCoat of arms.  aConquistador.  aCoral reef.  aCusco.  aDecree.  aDeity.  aDiego de Almagro.  aDjed.  aEdict.  aEdmundo O'Gorman.  aExpedition of the Thousand.  aFrancisco Pizarro.  aFrancisco de Vitoria.  aFriar.  aFrom Time Immemorial.  aFrontier.  aFuture.  aGiuseppe Mazzini.  aGonzalo Pizarro.  aGrammar.  aGreeks.  aHernando Pizarro.  aHypogeum.  aImperialism.  aInca Empire.  aInca Garcilaso de la Vega.  aIndigenous peoples of the Americas.  aIndo-Pacific.  aInterdependence.  aLactantius.  aLate Antiquity.  aLictor.  aLivy.  aMachiavellianism.  aMark Antony.  aMendes.  aMessina.  aMultitude.  aNaples.  aNarrative.